                <h2>Instructions to take care of your cat :</h2>
                <div>
                    <h3>Provide Proper Nutrition</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Food:</strong> Choose high-quality cat food appropriate for your cat's age, size,
                            and health. Kittens, adults, and senior cats have different dietary needs.</li>
                        <li><strong>Feeding Schedule:</strong> Feed your cat at consistent times each day. Cats often
                            prefer to eat several small meals throughout the day.</li>
                        <li><strong>Fresh Water:</strong> Always have fresh water available. Consider a cat water
                            fountain to encourage hydration, especially if your cat is reluctant to drink still water.
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <h3>Create a Safe Environment</h3>
                <div>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Shelter:</strong> Provide a warm, dry, and safe space inside your home.</li>
                        <li><strong>Hazard-Free Space:</strong> Ensure your home is free from potential hazards like
                            toxic plants, open windows, or accessible chemicals.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <h3>Maintain Good Health</h3>
                <div>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Veterinary Care:</strong> Regular check-ups with a vet can help catch and prevent
                            health issues. Keep up with vaccinations and parasite control.</li>
                        <li><strong>Spay/Neuter:</strong> Spaying or neutering your cat prevents unwanted litters and
                            reduces the risk of certain health problems.
                        </li>
                        <li><strong>Grooming</strong> Brush your cat regularly to reduce shedding and hairballs.
                            Long-haired breeds may require more frequent grooming.
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <h3>Safe environment:</h3>
